      "writtenOn": "2026-07-10T08:25:35Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I used `append_range` there which caused a CI run to fail\n\nhttps://jenkins.openbmc.org/job/ci-repository/140030/console\n```\nchar; _Alloc \u003d std::allocator\u003cunsigned char\u003e]’ at /usr/include/c++/15/bits/stl_vector.h:1690:27,\n    inlined from ‘std::vector\u003cunsigned char\u003e pldm::fw_update::makePkgV1_3_0()’ at ../tests/unit/bindings/cpp/firmware-update-test-v1-3-0.cpp:172:21:\n/usr/include/c++/15/bits/stl_uninitialized.h:273:31: error: ‘void* __builtin_memcpy(void*, const void*, long unsigned int)’ offset [50, 108] is out of the bounds [0, 50] [-Werror\u003darray-bounds\u003d]\n  273 |               __builtin_memcpy(std::__niter_base(__result),\n      |               ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~^~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n  274 |                                std::__niter_base(__first),\n      |                                ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n  275 |                                __n * sizeof(_ValT));\n      |                                ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\ncc1plus: all warnings being treated as errors\n```\n\nsince the failure was related to out-of-bounds access, reserving the capacity fixed it. Since it was part of a test code path i did not investigate further, i only needed the package and `append_range` is a more compact way to write it.\n\nBut since we won\u0027t be using that function anyways, i don\u0027t think it would make much of a difference to reserve capacity given the small size of the package here.\n\nIt would just be another constant needing adjustment if someone decides to make changes to the package contents.",
      "parentUuid": "09a7df1f_b6b2c0fe",
      "revId": "a90a50c9da30b60573d7fd825f03b2ba72aa1146",
      "serverId": "adbd0a64-1f21-4d83-b585-671fe73cb6e4"
